A black box in your car?
While road planners in the United States are struggling to find the money to repair the ageing highway infrastructure, many see a solution in the form of a small black box that is attached above the dashboard of your car.
The devices, which record every mile driven by a motorist and pass the information on to officials, are at the center of a controversial attempt in Washington and in government planning offices to overhaul the outdated system of financing major U.S. roads.
The generally uninteresting sector of major axis planning has suddenly given rise to a lively debate and heated alliances.
Libertarians have joined environmental groups in lobbying for the government to use the little boxes to keep track of the miles you drive, and possibly the road you drive, and then use the information to draft a tax bill.
The Tea Party is down.
The American Civil Liberties Union is also very concerned and expresses concern about the protection of privacy.
And while members of Congress can't agree on whether to continue, several states have not waited.
They're looking at how, over the next decade, they can move to a system where drivers pay based on the number of miles driven.
Thousands of motorists have already taken these black boxes, some of which are equipped with GPS monitoring systems, for a test drive.
This is absolutely essential for our nation.
 It's not like we have a choice , said Hasan Ikhrata, executive director of the Southern California Association of Governments, which expects the state to start recording the miles traveled by every Californian motorist by 2025.
There's going to be a change in the way we pay these taxes.
Technology is here to do that.
The pressure comes from the fact that the country's Highway Trust Fund, funded by taxes Americans pay at the pump, is financially dry.
Americans don't buy as much gas as they used to.
Cars can travel more than a mile with a gallon.
The federal tax itself, which is 18.4 cents a gallon, hasn't been raised in 20 years.
Politicians are reluctant to raise the tax, even by 1 cent, while gas prices are high.
 The tax on gasoline is simply not sustainable , said Lee Munnich, a transportation policy expert at the University of Minnesota.
His state recently had tracers installed on 500 cars to test a mile-paying system.
 This is the most logical alternative in the long term, he said.
Wonks calls this mileage usage charge.
It is not surprising that the idea appeals to urban liberals, since taxes could be used to change driving habits in ways that reduce congestion and emissions, for example.
California planners are interested in the system as they develop strategies to meet the goals set in the state's ambitious global warming laws.
But Representative Bill Shuster (R-Pa), chairman of the House Transportation Committee, said he also saw it as the most viable alternative in the long run.
Free market supporters of the Reason Foundation also like the idea of charging drivers for the mile.
 It is not just a tax that is sinking into a big black hole , said Adrian Moore, vice president of policy at the Reason Foundation.
People pay more directly for the benefits they receive.
The movement is also supported by two former US Transportation Secretaries who, in a 2011 report, urged Congress to go the mile-paying route.
The US Senate approved a $90 million pilot project last year that would have covered about 10,000 cars.
But the House of Lords President killed the proposal, responding to the concerns of rural legislators representing voters who have to travel many miles every day to get to work or to the city.
However, several states and large cities are making progress on their own.
The most determined is Oregon, which has mobilized 5,000 drivers to conduct the largest experiment in the country.
These motorists will soon be paying the state for mileage instead of taxes on gasoline.
Nevada has already completed a pilot project.
New York City is considering one.
Illinois is testing it on a limited number of trucks.
And the I-95 coalition, which includes 17 agencies involved in road transportation in states along the East Coast of the United States (including Maryland, Pennsylvania, Virginia, and Florida) is looking at how it could implement the change.
The concept is not universally successful.
In Nevada, where some 50 volunteer drivers recently fitted their cars with a device, drivers were concerned that the government might be able to track their every move.
"The concerns about Big Brother and things like that are a big problem", said Alauddin Khan, who heads strategic performance management at the Nevada Department of Transportation.
It's not something people want.
From the start of the trial, the ACLU of Nevada warned on its website:  It would be relatively easy to turn these devices into full-fledged location-tracking devices. 
There is no need to build a huge, cumbersome technological infrastructure that will inevitably be expanded to keep records of people's daily comings and goings.
Nevada is one of the few states that is now struggling to find affordable technology that would allow the state to know how many miles a car travels, but without knowing the exact location or time.
If we can do that, Khan added, citizens will feel more comfortable.
Research into this technology has led some state agencies to call in a small California startup called True Mileage.
The company was not originally intended to help motorists who pay taxes to the states.
It was looking to break into the emerging market of car insurance, where drivers would pay based on mileage.
But the devices she's testing have appealed to big-time planners because they don't use GPS and they provide a limited amount of information, which is periodically downloaded via modem.
"People will be more inclined to do this if you don't record their speed and locate them", said Ryan Morrison, CEO of True Mileage.
There have been serious errors in the pilot programmes of some States.
There are much less expensive and less intrusive methods of doing this.
In Oregon, planners are experimenting with offering drivers different choices.
They can choose a device with or without GPS.
They can still choose not to have a device at all, preferring instead to pay a fare based on the average number of miles traveled by all residents of the state.
Other states are hoping to sell the concept to unsuspecting citizens by allowing the devices to do more, rather than not enough.
In New York City, transportation officials are looking to develop a taxation system that would also be equipped to pay parking fees, provide insurance  pay-to-drive  and create a real-time speed data set from other drivers that motorists could use to avoid traffic jams.
 Drivers would be encouraged to participate because of the benefits the system offers them , said a paper on urban planning.
However, some transport planners wonder whether the whole debate on paying by mile is just a huge diversion.
At the Metropolitan Transportation Commission in the San Francisco Bay Area, officials say Congress could very simply manage the bankruptcy of the Highway Trust Fund by raising taxes on gasoline.
A one-off or additional annual tax could be imposed on drivers of hybrid vehicles and others whose vehicles do not consume much fuel, so that everyone pays his fair share.
"There is no need for radical surgery when you simply need aspirin", said Randy Rentschler, the commission's director of legislation and public affairs.
If we do that, hundreds of millions of motorists will be concerned about protecting their privacy and a whole bunch of other things.
