Defence Minister Rob Nicholson insisted that wounded soldiers were not summarily discharged from the Canadian Armed Forces, and stressed that a transition process was being followed by all soldiers before they returned to civilian life.
Attacked by the Liberals and the NDP in the House of Commons, Mr Nicholson assured that before their release, the military members were following a transition plan in collaboration with their superiors.
All wounded soldiers are receiving proper treatment to return to civilian life and none of them are released until they are ready, he said.
Critics accuse the government of saving money by not allowing injured military personnel - who do not meet the army's "universal service" rule requiring personnel to be able to perform a variety of tasks - to reach the 10-year eligibility period required for retirement benefits.
They cited two cases reported by The Canadian Press, including one of a soldier released last Friday.
Corporal David Hawkins, a London, Ontario, reservist with post-traumatic stress disorder, was discharged from the army despite his request to stay another year so he could receive a fully indexed pension.
His case came after that of Corporal Glen Kirkland, who told a parliamentary committee last month that he was pushed out before he was ready because he did not meet the rule of universal service.
Mr. Hawkins pointed out that a soldier could be prepared to leave, with plans and consultations, but that this was totally different from wanting to leave the ranks.
"I told them I wasn't ready", he said in an interview with The Canadian Press on Wednesday.
I asked for months if there was a way for me to stay, and they said no.
Since the start of major fighting in Afghanistan, the military has struggled to determine what latitude it can give to wounded soldiers who want to stay in the ranks but are not fit for combat.
Under current rules, soldiers who are seriously injured have up to three years to recover.
If they don't meet the criteria for deployment abroad, they may be forced out of the military.
Data presented to Parliament last year indicate that of the 1218 soldiers released for medical reasons, 199 had not reached the length of service required to qualify for retirement benefits.
Liberal veteran spokesman Jim Karygiannis called for Corporal Hawkins' reinstatement on Wednesday, while New Democrat Jack Harris called for an immediate end to "this shameful practice".
