NSA spying: US has "gone too far", admits Kerry
The United States has sometimes gone "too far" in spying, Secretary of State John Kerry has admitted, in this first admission from Washington in the midst of a controversy with Europe over the massive data collection by the National Security Agency (NSA).
After ten days of scandal, revelations and denials between the United States and its European allies, this is the first time that a U.S. government official has explicitly admitted to controversial practices in the NSA's interception of communications and data in Europe.
"In some cases, I'll concede to you, as the president did, some of these actions have gone too far and we're going to make sure that doesn't happen again in the future", John Kerry said at a conference in London, which he attended from Washington on Thursday, Oct. 31.
In his speech, which was broadcast in the presence of his British counterpart William Hague, the US chief of state at length justified intelligence and intelligence-gathering practices by the need to combat terrorism and prevent possible attacks.
Referring to the attacks of 11 September 2001, the Madrid attacks of March 2004 and the London attacks of July 2005, John Kerry said that the US authorities had since thwarted many terrorist attacks through interception of communications and intelligence gathering.
"We have actually prevented planes from crashing, buildings from exploding and people from being killed, because we were able to know about these plans in advance", the US diplomat argued.
And, John Kerry told the Europeans, "I assure you that in this process innocent people have not been deceived".
But we're trying to gather information.
"And yes, in some cases it went too far in an inappropriate way", admitted the Secretary of State, who had already spoken out on the international scandal during a tour last week in Paris, London and Rome.
He assured Thursday evening that President Obama was "determined to try to clarify and to review these practices so that no one feels deceived".
But the controversy between Americans and Europeans continued to flare up this week with new revelations in the press.
