But the head of the powerful NSA, General Keith Alexander, denied that his intelligence agency had intercepted tens of millions of communications of European citizens.
He even sent the bullet back to European intelligence agencies who would have seized those communications, before handing them over to the NSA.
This would involve "military operations" in countries where these NATO allies are cooperating with the United States and would not be aimed at Europe at all, said General Alexander.
And the controversy spread to Asia on Friday.
