For their own funerals, more and more French people choose cremation rather than burial: 53 percent, according to an Ipsos survey of 1,009 people on September 6 and 7, instead of 47 percent.
For the funeral of a loved one, the opposite is true: the French prefer burial (53% versus 47%).
If they're unlucky enough to lose a child, only 15% of them choose cremation.
In his book Death in Ashes, philosopher Damien Le Guay, vice-chairman of the National Funeral Ethics Committee, emphasizes the "violence" of cremation for survivors.
There is, with cremation, "a violence to the body of the loved one", which will be "reduced to a pile of ashes" in a very short time, not after a process of decomposition, which "would accompany the phases of mourning".
There is also "symbolic violence", which is the "de-identification of singularity and distinctive signs" reduced to the "anonymity" of ashes.
Why is what is accepted without difficulty in some Nordic and Protestant countries still poorly lived in France?
"Because cremation is a new phenomenon", answers Marie-Frédérique Bacqué, president of the Society of Pathology and author of Apprivoiser la mort.
It has been tolerated by the Catholic Church only since 1963, which has limited attempts to tame it.
