The annual Ipsos survey shows a very strong commitment to the organization of the ceremony.
77% of French people want a marriage for their loved ones, whether it be religious (53%), or civil (24%).
Now 73% of those who chose cremation wish to have a ceremony.
66% of atheists and non-believers also want it.
Crematoriums have adapted to this change in society.
"For about ten years they have tried to prevent families from the violence of waiting, doing nothing, for an hour and a half, immediately followed by the delivery of the ashes", observes Michaud-Nérard.
Seventy percent of institutions now offer ceremonial masters, who perform the following rituals in the presence of the body: greeting the assembly, naming the deceased, connecting him with others, evoking him, giving meaning to his death, organizing the farewell.
This has been the case at the crematorium of Père Lachaise since 1998.
The masters of the ceremony are often people who have converted.
There are also former Catholic priests.
