George Kerevan: The split of Europe gives Scots a choice
Another day, another disturbing story of independence.
This time we are told that an independent Scotland would have to join the European Free Movement Area in order to join the EU.
And now we hear stories of passport control at Berwick and a border of barbed wire along Hadrian's Wall.
While it is true that the Strathclyde newspaper pointed to the possible economic benefits of greater freedom of movement with the rest of Europe, it was not in the headlines (and it was to be expected).
Nor has anyone said that EU Member States spend a lot of time bypassing their formal rules when it suits them.
Since Scotland is not part of the Schengen area at the moment, continued non-compliance with the rules would be a small concession that Brussels could offer in return for everything it wants from the Scots.
So this is a story that is not a story.
And a story so old that it's now frozen: I first heard the gossip that independence means passport control over 40 years ago.
Yet, an interesting point has been overlooked in this interpretation of an old dust fairy tale.
Why should an independent Scotland follow the directions of Europe, really?
Why trade the yoke of London for that of Brussels, especially now?
The real news for Europe is that the grand post-war plan for European unification is definitely deadlocked.
With the euro crisis, the Europe Project is officially dead.
Across Europe, parties opposed to the EU or advocating for the euro to be abandoned as a common currency are gaining ground.
Even in Germany, the Eurosceptic Alternative for Germany party, founded only this year and coming out of nowhere, gathered almost five million votes in the federal elections in September and drove the Liberal Democratic Party (equivalent to our Liberal Democrats) out of the Bundestag.
There has always been national opposition to the project of creating a federal Europe.
However, the current economic crisis has marked a turning point.
The austerity imposed by Berlin and the European Central Bank, coupled with the strain on national economies through membership of the single currency, has led many people to think that the Europe Project has gone too far.
The euro crisis has little to do with national governments running excessive budget deficits. This was only true for Greece.
The European system has instead imposed on its members favourable exchange rates for German exporters, which German politicians want to keep.
Without the possibility of devaluing the national currency, the countries of southern Europe are left with an intrinsic productivity problem vis-à-vis Germany.
The only recourse is to make dismal cuts in public wages and expenditure  encouraged by Berlin.
Beyond the current budgetary and monetary problems, there is a deeper unease about productivity in Europe.
As a result of the green energy policies imposed by Brussels, which are a reason for subsidizing French and German energy companies at the expense of the consumer, European industry pays twice as much for electricity and four times as much for gas as the United States.
This is a cost-rewarding disadvantage, as we have already seen in Grangemouth.
All the wage freezes in the world will not prevent the European petrochemical industry from being penalized by cheap American shale gas.
As a result, the revolt is brewing, especially in France, one of the great leaders of the EU.
After the war, the French political elite saw the EU as a means of controlling Germany and putting Paris on an equal footing with Washington.
But Berlin no longer needs Paris as a passport of political legitimacy and has imposed its own economic policy on Europe, leaving the struggling French economy to struggle.
The result: Marine Le Pen's far-right party, the anti-European National Front, has just won a crucial by-election, returning the Socialists to power in third place.
The National Front is now the most popular party in France with 24 per cent of the vote  a timely warning to the British Labour Party that it cannot assume that a split on the right will automatically favour the left.
What is Marine Le Pen doing with her newfound popularity among the French white working class?
It wants to use the European elections next year to create a single anti-money and anti-European bloc in the European Parliament.
If the anti-European parties do well in these elections, which is very possible, such a bloc could control the European Parliament for the first time.
I think that very soon the anti-European and anti-monetary sentiment in Europe will unite and will eventually kill the euro.
The EU will not disappear, but it will return to something more like  the Europe of (sovereign) nations  free privileged by General de Gaulle.
Germany and some of its satellite economies may retain the euro, but France and southern Europe will regain their own currency.
I expect the United Kingdom to distance itself from this project, and I hope it will turn a blind eye to the United States.
However, Washington's growing interest in the Pacific suggests that Britain will be left behind in the Atlantic.
What about Scotland?
We can decide to be a region of Little England (essentially).
Or we can defend our own economic interests, which includes sending people to Berlin and Brussels.
I believe that Scotland could settle for a freer European agreement provided we kept our own currency.
Cooperation with other like-minded countries would be easier in a non-federal Europe of Nations.
If not, we should follow Norway and maintain our economic independence.
The SNP government in Scotland is  and is notably  the most successful anti-austerity political movement in Europe, having won a dramatic majority in 2011 based on its opposition to the dark cuts proposed (and implemented) by Labour Chancellor Alistair Darling and the Conservative/Liberal Democrat coalition that followed.
It would be ridiculous for Scotland to vote for independence now if it is to accept the austerity imposed by Berlin and Brussels.
Early puberty - aging early
Studies show that African-American and Hispanic girls tend to reach puberty earlier than white girls.
Physical changes do not mean puberty is imminent
There is no evidence that hormones or other chemicals are responsible
Experts believe the obesity epidemic may be a trigger for early puberty
The trend towards early puberty is not as pronounced among boys
Former CNN correspondent Pat Etheridge is a journalist specializing in family and child health issues.
Should a mother worry if her daughter's breasts and pubic hair start growing at 7 or 8?
At the annual conference of the American Academy of Pediatrics held this week in Orlando, Florida, paediatric endocrinologist Dr. Paul Kaplowitz explained that these early physical changes are quite common among young Americans and represent a new norm.
 I spend a lot of time reassuring parents  generally, this does not indicate a rapid shift towards full puberty , Kaplowitz said.
Clear signs of development, such as breast budding, hair under the arms and in the pubic area, and body odors, appear earlier in girls.
But there's been only a slight advance in the age of first menstruation over the last four decades.
In the United States, the average age is 12 and a half years, compared with 12 years three quarters of the time in 1970.
Once the breast begins to develop, it takes at least two to three years for the first menstrual period to appear, said Kaplowitz, who also wrote Early Puberty in Girls: The Essential Guide to Coping with This Common Problem.
Time is the most accurate test of how puberty will develop.
There is debate about what constitutes the actual onset of puberty, but it is considered  early  when breast development is accompanied by sudden growth before the age of 8 years.
In most cases, development slows or stops -- something a pediatrician can monitor closely.
A faster progression may warrant tests by an endocrinologist to rule out serious problems such as tumors or cysts.
There are treatments to delay the onset of the first menstrual period and prevent other consequences: premature bone aging that can slow growth and small size in adulthood.
Recommendations for medication and hormone treatment are based on the child's age, rate of development, rate of growth and emotional maturity.
Psychosocial aspects are also important.
Kaplowitz is cautious about medication but acknowledges that  controlling puberty can alleviate some behavioral problems and girls' feelings of being different from others .
The other big problem is understandable: Parents simply don't want their very young daughters to have their period.
 They fear the risk of pregnancy or even how they will handle hygiene issues , Kaplowitz said.
"It was a shock", recalls one woman whose daughter had her first period at the age of 10.
Even though there were signs and we talked about menstruation, she wasn't emotionally prepared.
She came home from school scared and upset to be the first among her friends.
There are many theories that have been made public about the causes of premature puberty.
Yet, there is no consistent theory that hormones in milk or other foods, chemicals in the environment, or the sexual messages portrayed in the media are responsible.
Boys, like girls, reach puberty earlier.
Kaplowitz says the most credible hypothesis is that there is an obesity epidemic.
He was involved in a study of girls aged 6 to 9 years old that linked the percentage of fat mass to the onset of puberty.
Other discoveries support this conclusion, but there are many other factors that influence it.
African-American and Hispanic girls tend to reach puberty earlier than white girls in this country.
There are various explanations.
On a global scale, the mechanisms of early puberty seem to be influenced by everything from economic conditions to climate to genes.
Another problem: Although boys have facial and pubic hair at a younger age, the trend toward early puberty is not as pronounced as in girls.
Other doctors attending the AAP conference stressed the complexity of the subject.
Acne and pubic hair are common, even in infants and toddlers.
 We need to be careful about how we identify the true onset of puberty , said Dr. Lawrence Silverman, a pediatric endocrinologist at Goryeb Children's Hospital in Morristown, New Jersey.
Parents should not hesitate to ask their pediatrician for advice on how to communicate with their child.
 This may mean having a conversation earlier than planned , Kaplowitz explained.
If you remain calm, your child will generally respond well.
Girls who are experiencing early puberty need to be reassured that even when it happens sooner than expected, the process is a part of life.
