The new anti-nicotine vaccine could take away the pleasure of smoking
Scientists have developed an anti-nicotine vaccine that could suppress the pleasure of smoking a cigarette.
A single dose of the vaccine was able to protect mice from nicotine addiction for life.
More tests are needed before human trials begin, but Professor Ronald Crystal of Weill Cornell Medical College in New York said early signs were encouraging.
"We really hope that this kind of vaccination strategy can help millions of smokers who have tried to quit, exhausting all the methods available on the market today, but are discovering that their addiction is strong enough to overcome these different approaches", said Professor Cornell.
The new vaccine contains a harmless virus that has been modified to carry the genetic information needed to design anti-nicotine antibodies.
The virus selectively infects the liver cells, which then begin to produce a steady stream of antibodies.
The antibodies track down all the nicotine molecules in the bloodstream and neutralize them before they reach the brain, preventing the smoker from getting his dose of nicotine.
In the tests, the vaccinated mice that were then given nicotine continued to function normally.
But the unvaccinated mice were calmer, the researchers said, a sign that nicotine had reached their brains.
The experiments are described in the journal Science Translational Medicine.
Previous tobacco vaccines have proven ineffective because they contained antibodies.
The injections had to be repeated so frequently to keep the antibody levels high that they were too expensive and impractical.
But the cost of the new vaccine should be much lower because it turns liver cells into antibody factories.
Professor Crystal said that if the future vaccine for human use were completely safe, it could be given to children before they are tempted to try a cigarette, thus preventing any nicotine addiction.
But it is more likely to be used by smokers who want to quit.
 They will know that if they start smoking again, they will not enjoy it because of the anti-nicotine vaccine, and this can help them to lose their bad habit , he added.
