How biometrics will invade our lives
No more passwords to type into her smartphone or pay for her shopping?
Researchers in the United States, France and Japan predict a future where we will be recognized by biometric sensors in phones and computers.
Bernard Didier, deputy director general of Morpho, even believes that "the century will be biometric".
Only biometrics will ensure the identity of a person making transactions in a universe as transversal and transnational as the Internet.
Privacy organizations confirm this biometric craze, but are concerned.
In 2011 alone, the French National Commission for Information and Freedom authorized 774 systems for the recognition of fingerprints, hand shape or hand vein network in companies, government offices, canteens...
"Everyone will soon be able to identify themselves, anywhere, anytime", says Justin Brookman, director of consumer privacy at the Center for Democracy and Technology (CDT) in Washington.
Why is there such optimism in some people and such pessimism in others?
Biometrics will rely on new techniques, which will enable new services to be provided to citizens and consumers.
Today, in France, the most widely used biometric data are fingerprints, hand contours and the vein network of the palm or fingers.
But each of these techniques has its limitations.
"For example, some people who work with concrete have very damaged fingers and their fingerprints are unreadable", says Philippe Robin, technical director of identity at Thales Communications & Security.
And the collection and the checking of the vein network and the contour of the hand presuppose a voluntary and precise gesture of the people.
This is both a safety factor - you cannot capture this data without them knowing - and a disadvantage: the procedure sometimes has to be repeated and therefore takes time.
As a result, research has been carried out for some 20 years into other methods, such as facial recognition or iris (the colored part of the eye).
The increased precision of sensors and the computing power of computers required for data analysis have made these techniques operational.
Facial recognition has increased tenfold in accuracy over the past five years, calculates Cyrille Bataller, director of Accenture's R&D laboratories in Europe.
With our help, the UK and the Netherlands have deployed automated border crossings using facial recognition.
It's now possible to identify a moving face or iris.
"We are currently doing research on voice recognition or walking with sound sensors, but we need a quiet environment", says Sridhar Iyengar, director of security research at Intel Labs.
DNA, a unique and unmistakable marker, also raises hopes and concerns.
"At the current state of knowledge, it can be considered the ultimate biometric data", confirms Sophie Vulliet-Tavernier, Director of Studies, Innovation and Prospects at the CNIL.
But DNA analysis is still very time-consuming and very expensive.
NEC offers the police forensic services a suitcase costing 90,000 euros to analyze DNA samples at a crime scene and in one hour.
The uses of biometrics fall into two groups: identification (recognizing a person among others) and authentication (assuring that the person is who he or she claims to be).
The identification process has so far been concerned with issuing identity papers: the biometric elements (fingerprints, photo, iris) must be compared with the information the State has on all citizens already registered.
This helps to ensure that someone is not trying to steal someone else's identity.
This principle of comparison can have other applications.
NEC offers VIP recognition at the entrance of a hotel or shop.
"We take the images from the surveillance cameras and compare them with the photos of celebrities that circulate freely on the Internet", explains Dany Nassif, NEC France's business development manager for biometric identification solutions.
Another use is to photograph a quidam in line at a store, track its progress using facial recognition, and calculate the waiting time.
Authentication was initially concerned with physical access (border, protected premises, canteens...) or logical access (opening a computer).
More recently, attendance checks have been added.
"A biometric pointer avoids the phenomenon of a boyfriend pointing to another", explains Cyrille Bataller of Accenture.
But increasingly, authentication will also apply to transactions, especially those made from internet-connected devices.
In Japan, it is already possible to withdraw money from some dealers by inserting a card and placing your hand on a biometric reader - this gesture replaces typing the secret code.
A similar technique is being tested in Villeneuve-d'Ascq and Angoulême by Natural Security in partnership with banks and major retailers: when paying in a store with a credit card, the customer does not type his code, but inserts his finger into a vein-scanning reader.
The experiment is planned to last six months.
If it is conclusive, biometric readers could soon be available to French traders.
Guidance for users
There are three ways to make biometrics appealing to the general public.
The first is to explain that it can save time.
"If, thanks to biometrics, a customer stays at the checkout 30 seconds less, it's a good thing", explains the manager of a large area.
The second is to offer personalized services, so in a few years, a voice server will be able to recognize your voice and offer you customized options.
Finally, it should reassure by highlighting the precautions taken to protect the databases.
"Fingerprints are stored on a first server; the identities of the people are in a second base: the correlation between the two numbers is encrypted and stored in a highly secure box, which is locked if you try to move it", lists Philippe Robin of Thales.
But, without extensive research, it is impossible to know whether these discourses really convince users.
Privacy experts, on the other hand, continue to be concerned.
"Advances in facial recognition, the proliferation of surveillance cameras, and the huge amount of photos available on Facebook, Flickr or Picasa, make me fear the worst: widespread surveillance", predicts Andrew Patrick, the Privacy Commissioner of Canada.
