Scientists have recently uncovered how the movements of a dog's tail are linked to its mood.
Previous studies had found that happy dogs moved their tail more to the right (from the dog's point of view), while nervous dogs moved their tail more to the left.
But now scientists say that dogs can detect these subtle differences and respond to them.
Professor Georgio Vallortigara, a neuroscientist at the University of Trento, said: "It is well known that in humans the left and right sides of the brain are involved in different ways in the stimuli that arouse positive or negative emotions".
Here we tried to see what it was like in other species.
He added that, as in humans, in dogs the right side of the brain was responsible for left-handed movement and vice versa, and that both hemispheres played different roles in emotions.
To learn more about how dogs react to the disorderly movements of other dogs' tails, researchers tracked animals while they watched movies featuring other dogs.
They measured the heart rate of the animals and analyzed their behavior.
It will probably not be long before we understand why their tail sometimes goes to one side and sometimes to the other.
Professor Vallortigara explained:  We showed dogs films featuring other dogs  either a naturalistic version or a silhouette to avoid any other confusion  and we were able to manipulate the movement of the tail and present it as going further to the left or to the right. 
When the animals saw a dog with no expression wagging its tail to the right (from the dog's point of view), they were perfectly relaxed.
But when they spotted a tail that was mostly veering to the left (again from the dog's point of view as he was waving the tail), their heart rate sped up and they looked anxious.
Professor Vallortigara said he didn't think the dogs were deliberately communicating with each other through these movements.
Rather, he believes that dogs know from experience what movements they should or should not be concerned about.
He added:  If you repeatedly encounter other dogs and notice that, most of the time, their tail movement to one side is associated with a more friendly attitude and the right side leads to a less friendly attitude, you will react according to that experience. 
The researchers say that the findings could help owners, veterinarians, and trainers to better understand the emotions of their pets.
Dog behaviour expert John Bradshaw, a visiting professor at the University of Bristol's School of Veterinary Science, said that this was not the first study to examine the importance of left and right in the canine species.
Last year, a team at the University of Lincoln found that dogs turned their heads to the left when they looked at an aggressive dog and to the right when they looked at a happy dog.
And in another scientific study done by the University of Victoria in Canada, he said:  Dogs were more likely to go to a robot dog when its tail moved to the left rather than to the right, instead of becoming anxious  the opposite of what was found in the Italian study. 
He said that the differences might be due to the fact that the dogs in the different studies did not fully consider the animals in the films or the robot dogs as dogs.
A study of how dogs react to real dogs could be useful, he explained.
 Although many evidence from different mammals indicates that the two sides of the brain are used for different purposes, many details still need to be clarified  and dogs are no exception , he said.
However, given how easily their behavior can be recorded, it will probably not be long before we understand why their tail sometimes moves to one side and sometimes to the other.
