A team of biologists led by the New York-based Wildlife Conservation Society has identified a new species of humpback dolphin off the northern coast of Australia.
Thibaut Bouveroux, a scientific mission officer at the Observatory for the Conservation and Study of Marine Animals and Environments (OCEAMM), reports on the discovery and explains the long process of identifying new species.
Does the discovery of this new species of humpback dolphin surprise you?
That's good news, but it doesn't surprise me.
Whereas in the past species were described and identified on the basis of morphology, anatomy and geography, today the development of new tools such as genetics allows us to improve our knowledge of the sciences of species classification.
And it is not impossible that such advances in genetics and molecular biology will challenge the classification or belonging of a species to a genus, a family, or even an order.
In the early 19th century, morphologists classified animals, based on the morphological differences between species.
Today, some of these rankings are being challenged by advances in genetics.
Similarly, two species which are morphologically very similar have been distinguished by genetic means.
This is the case with the newly identified species.
About a decade ago, the scientific community recognized two species belonging to this subfamily - the Pacific humpback dolphin and the Atlantic humpback whale.
Recent analyses have made it possible to distinguish four species.
Why is this a discovery of such importance as the Wildlife Conservation Society has claimed?
From a conservation point of view, it is essential to know about these genetic differences in order to protect the species and thus its genetic variability.
While this population was known to researchers for a long time, they did not know that it was part of a new species, found only in this area.
So if a mass death problem caused by a viral epidemic or accidental capture occurs in the region, we could be dealing with a species extinction, rather than a local extinction of a population of a more widely distributed species on Earth.
This loss of genetic heritage would be much more problematic.
A species is considered endangered or endangered depending on the number of individuals on Earth, i.e. the stock, and the possibility of it recovering from neighbouring stocks.
As regards Sousa chinensis, from which the population of the newly discovered species is derived, its stock has automatically become smaller, making it more vulnerable.
Why is it so rare to discover new species of marine mammals?
Marine mammals are at the top of the food chain.
They live in homogeneous, open habitats, where there is a lot of genetic exchange between populations and individuals.
This gene-bonding restricts the creation of new species.
Conversely, more closed ecosystems promote genetic isolation, which may eventually lead to the creation of new species.
It should be noted that the marine environment is the least known environment.
We'd rather send robots to Mars than find out what lives in the Mariana Trench, only seven miles above the surface of the sea.
We spend more money looking for life on other planets than we do marine research, and it's about time that changed.
RBS suspends two traders on the foreign exchange market
Royal Bank of Scotland has suspended two traders from its foreign exchange market division, according to two sources familiar with the matter, which shows once again that the global investigation by regulators into suspicions of currency market manipulation is beginning to bear fruit.
Some of the world's largest banks, including UBS, Barclays, Deutsche Bank and RBS, confirmed that they were cooperating with regulators in their investigations into the world's largest financial market, where US$5.3 trillion changes hands every day.
The two traders are the first RBS employees to be suspended as part of the broadening of the investigation which echoes the Libor interbank rate manipulation scandal.
The bank, which declined to comment on the suspensions, confirmed this month that it had received requests for information from regulators.
 The ongoing investigation into this matter is ongoing and we are fully cooperating with the FCA and other regulators , a bank representative said two weeks ago.
Last month, sources familiar with the matter said that RBS had passed on files of emails and instant messages sent to and by a former trader to the UK regulator, the Financial Conduct Authority.
This trader, Richard Usher, left RBS in 2010 and was reportedly suspended from his position as European head of spot currency trading at JPMorgan.
Rohan Ramchandani, European head of cash foreign exchange trading at Citi, was laid off this week, while Matt Gardiner, senior currency trader at Barclays and UBS, was suspended by Standard Chartered this week.
None of these traders have been charged.
Mr. Usher's file included instant messages sent to and by bankers working at Barclays and Citigroup, sources familiar with the file added.
UBS said this week it had filed a lawsuit against some of its employees after Swiss regulator Finma said it was investigating suspicions of foreign exchange manipulation in a number of Swiss banks.
At least six authorities worldwide - the European Commission, Finma, the Swiss competition authority Weko, the FCA, the US Department of Justice and the Hong Kong Monetary Authority - are investigating allegations made about bankers who have conspired to manipulate rates in the foreign exchange market.
HSBC, Citigroup, JPMorgan and Credit Suisse have also launched internal investigations or received requests for information from regulators, sources familiar with the matter said.
Banks are scanning instant messages and emails sent over the years to find cases of wrongdoing.
The news of these investigations has shaken traders in a sector that has been one of the biggest drivers of growth in investment bank trading units in recent years but has been challenged this year due to low currency volatility that limits opportunities for speculators.
Some bankers have tried to downplay the issue by saying that it is almost impossible to manipulate the vast, highly liquid foreign exchange market, but senior traders explain that this is not necessarily true.
One senior trader said that despite the high volume of daily foreign exchange transactions, the fragmentation of liquidity between trading platforms and the increasing use by banks of their own internal platforms  explains why it is possible to start having an impact on the market at low cost .
The news came on the same day that Credit Suisse announced it had fired a trader working at its London Stock Exchange office this week after he caused a $6 million loss at the end of last year.
The Bank promptly informed the relevant authorities and cooperated with the regulators.
 We are convinced that the trader acted alone and that the case was brought under control , said a representative of Credit Suisse.
