Back in black and white for Marie Chouinard, who presents at Danse Danse her two new group choreographies: the first inspired by the inks and poems of Henri Michaux, the second inspired by the famous piano solos Gymnopédies by Satie.
An evening where you can see the whole Chouinard prism, from art to tics and black to ink to white.
A white screen is used as a backdrop.
On the carpet, so white, in the vast space that is the Maisonneuve Theatre, advances, profile, thin as a line and dressed in black, a body.
On the screen, an ink by Henri Michaux is projected.
The body, simple trait, takes its shape.
And this shape will be the whole room: an envelope of physical imitations of the drawings.
The dancers, all dressed in black, only their hands and faces uncovered, wait on either side of the playing field, rush when the next figure appears, embody it, and come running.
This black and white play by Henri Michaux is performed in solo relay, in unison group (a mass that does solo), in a large group of twelve solos where each performs his sign.
One thought is "Morning Glory", where Chouinard performed a series of choreographic tasks on posters, laid out in a line in the foreground.
It's the same principle, the giant PowerPoint version.
Here, the music is loud, percussion and electric guitars.
The energy is high, the pace is always fast.
There will be a break when Carol Prieur will take refuge under the dance floor, to deliver, microphone in hand, without sobriety or restraint, a part of Michaux's poem, monochord and monotone in the cry, and continue dancing.
And the music to go back, and the sequence to go back.
This loud, energetic sound, if prolonged, eventually causes deafness and numbness.
So does the regularity of visual rhythm.
There are some beautiful flashes - image creation has always been a strength at Chouinard - like those hair that twitches or those black fabrics that lengthen the lines.
But the choreographic approach lacks composition.
It seems that the choreographer, instead of going to meet Michaux's work, has imposed herself, with her tics.
As a result, the bodies appear flat in front of the drawings.
Michaux's inks, like Gestalt shapes, open up a wider and more gigantic imagination than dance, more porous.
Only the ending, in negative, with its dancers chopped by stroboscopic light and the white signs in a theater suddenly dark, touches on the magic.
The audience liked it, the reception was warm.
Gymnopedies, after the intersection, is richer.
The stage is partly covered in grey, the dancers and a piano are covered in fabrics, like furniture in an abandoned house.
At the piano, dancers take turns to play the music.
Their musical awkwardness, touching, gives a real fragility.
On stage, couples are performing in a romantic, sensual, even erotic, duo.
Group work, small solo transitions, moving ensembles, choirs, writing is less binary.
Clowns appear, as familiar to Chouinard, with red noses, in highly polarized male-female love parades.
Loves are carnivorous, elusive or gambler.
The gestures, the laughter and the small cries beautifully transpose the archaic, the graceful and the ridiculous of the bodies into coitus, the fading beings.
But the play takes off after the salvation.
A clown returns to the stage when the audience leaves.
There, everything becomes permissible: the fourth wall falls, the explored universes overlap, the dancers cavort, descend among the spectators, gloss, smoke, short-circuit, play codes of applause, stretch the sauce in a cleverly calculated mess that remains sensual.
Joy and madness sweat, and it's Chouinard's art to contaminate the public.
