For 21 years, Georges Bwelle watched his sick father alternate periods of unconsciousness and visiting hospitals that were not equipped to help him.
Jamef Bwelle was injured in a car accident in 1981 near Yaoundé, the capital of Cameroon.
At first, he had only a broken arm, but he contracted an infection that spread to his brain, creating a hematoma that would haunt him for the rest of his life.
 There were no neurosurgeons in Cameroon , said Georges Bwelle.
We would have taken him abroad if we had enough money.
Instead, Dr. Bwelle spent years escorting his father to crowded clinics and hospitals, so that he could get whatever treatment he could benefit from.
 It is not easy , Mr Bwelle adds.
You can leave the house at 5:00, rush to the hospital to be the first, and you're not the first.
There are a lot of patients.
People can die because they wait too long.
The situation hasn't changed much since Dr Bwelle's father died in 2002.
In Cameroon, there is only 1 doctor for every 5,000 inhabitants, according to the World Health Organization.
By comparison, the ratio in the United States is 1 doctor per 413 inhabitants.
And even if they could see a doctor, many Cameroonians could not afford the consultation.
Two out of five people in the country live below the poverty line, and nearly three-quarters of the country's health expenditure is spent in the private sector.
 The only problem they have is poverty , Dr Bwelle explained.
And because of poverty, they can't enjoy life.
After seeing his father and so many of his countrymen suffer, Dr. Bwelle was determined to try and change the course of things.
Dr. Georges Bwelle and his team of volunteers performed over 700 free surgeries last year.
He became a doctor himself, working as a vascular surgeon at the Yaoundé Central Hospital.
And he started a non-profit humanitarian organization, ASCOVIME, that goes to rural areas on weekends to provide free health care.
Since 2008, he and his group of volunteers have helped nearly 32,000 people.
Almost every Friday, with about 30 others, they pile into vans after fixing medical supplies on the roof and cross rough terrain to reach the villages where help is most needed.
Luck doesn't always follow.
They had to push their vehicles over rivers or muddy tracks.
But when they arrive, they are greeted as heroes - the community throws a party, sings and dances, and offers them the best accommodations available.
In these villages, free health care is a good reason to celebrate, and Dr Bwelle  with his big smile and overflowing energy  is more than happy to join in the festivities.
The next morning, the team starts seeing hundreds of patients.
 We receive 500 people each visit , said Mr Bwelle.
They sometimes live 60 kilometers from the village, and they come on foot.
In this itinerant hospital, various health care services are provided.
Many people are receiving treatment for malaria, tuberculosis, malnutrition, diabetes, parasites, and sexually transmitted diseases.
Others may receive crutches, a collected pair of glasses or a free birth certificate  document necessary to go to school, but many poor families simply cannot afford to buy it.
At night, the team performs simple surgical procedures under local anesthesia.
Surgeries are usually performed in a school, town hall or home; after the procedure, the patient gets up and goes to the wake room to give his place to the next person.
With the lighting of the generator, the operating room and the sterilization of the equipment, Dr. Bwelle and his volunteers are working until the early hours of Sunday morning.
It's a grueling rhythm, but the village musicians usually help the team stay motivated.
 They are beating on drums all night to keep us awake so we can continue working , Mr Bwelle explained.
On Sunday, the team returns to the city, tired but proud of the work they have done.
The group, made up of Cameroonian doctors and medical students, performed 700 free surgeries last year, and they know that their presence can make a difference for those they help.
One man explained that the free surgery he had undergone to treat a hernia would allow him to work again.
"It will change my future and that of my family", the man said.
In addition to running this travelling hospital and working as a surgeon at the hospital, Dr Bwelle also works at night in private medical offices around Yaoundé.
He explains that this second job is the one that finances his association by 60%, the rest being covered by private donations.
"I don't know when he sleeps", said Katie O'Malley, a second-year medical student at Drexel University in Philadelphia and a volunteer in Dr. Bwelle's group.
He's still in the hospital or trying to raise money for his charity so he can run these campaigns.
For medical students and nursing students like Katie O'Malley, who come from the United States and Europe to join Mr. Bwelle on his missions, it's a learning opportunity in the field that they don't have at home.
 We could have been involved in operations to help with the sponge blood or to get the instruments to Dr Bwelle , Ms O'Malley explained.
It's not something you get to do in America when you're a sophomore in med school.
Student volunteers usually pay for their journey to Cameroon, and often arrive with collected medical equipment.
But once in Yaoundé, their boarding, transportation and education are taken care of by Dr. Bwelle.
"He is a hero, there is no doubt about it", said Katie O'Malley.
He gives his life for this association, and his desire to help the Cameroonian people is not going to die.
For Dr Bwelle, the relatively constant workload is not a problem.
Helping others to live happily by fulfilling the promise he made to his father is something that brings him immense joy.
 I am so happy when I do this job , Mr Bwelle added.
And I think about my father.
I hope he sees what I'm doing.
Making people laugh and relieving pain are the reasons I do this.
