Australian woman appeals her sentence in Thailand
A 21-year-old Sydney resident who was sentenced to 15 days in prison in Phuket for falsely claiming she was assaulted by a taxi driver has appealed the verdict and was released on bail.
Stevie Rochelle Bamford was first found guilty by a Phuket Provincial Court on June 15 of making false statements after she told Thai police that a local taxi driver, accompanied by two other men who were controlling her, had assaulted her early on Sunday, June 10.
However, surveillance footage later revealed that she had returned safely to her hotel after separating from her Australian boyfriend.
Phuket police questioned Bamford for two days before she confessed to making up the story out of thin air.
She was held in a cell at the local police station before her trial.
Bamford was sentenced to a 15-day prison sentence in a low-security detention center on the outskirts of Phuket rather than a women's prison.
She is the daughter of former Australian rugby league player Peter Tunks, who appealed to the Canberra Foreign Office to help his daughter.
Tunks told the Sydney Sunday Telegraph that the whole family was extremely concerned for their daughter's well-being and wanted her to return to Australia.
"We obviously had a very anxious time, but we hope to get her home safely as soon as possible", Tunks said.
Bamford appealed the verdict and was released after a 50,000 baht bail was paid.
In Australia, the press reported that she was on holiday in the Krabi region of southern Thailand.
Thai judicial sources said Bamford was represented by a local Phuket lawyer, but warned that the appeal could lead to a harsher sentence of up to two years in prison and incarceration in an adult prison.
However, following the recent murder in Phuket of Australian travel agent Michelle Smith, Thailand may also be looking to repair its deteriorated image with tourists, which could lead to an acquittal.
French police will arrest Anderlecht fans who came with cars other than RSCA
The French police have decided to impose strict rules regarding the match between Royal Sporting Club Anderlecht and Paris Saint-Germain scheduled for Tuesday, Marie Verbeke, the spokeswoman for the Brussels police area, said on Friday afternoon.
The Belgian RSCA supporters who wish to attend this Champions League match will have to use the RSCA's travel system.
"The bus convoy will be escorted by the police from a former border post in Rekem to the PSG stadium", the spokeswoman said.
The same procedure will be followed on the return journey.
"If other fans had any intention of travelling to Paris by other means, the French police prefecture has announced that measures have been taken to arrange for arrests and even sight-guards", Marie Verbeke said.
Living together in French, the challenge of the Marguerite-Bourgeoys school board
At the Marguerite-Bourgeoys school board, 62% of pupils have a mother tongue other than French.
This is what prompted a consultation with parents, pupils, teachers and education staff a year ago to consider ways of better integrating pupils who live in different cultures.
The school board has just unveiled its vision for "Living Together in French".
The organisation Vision diversité has been walking around schools for a year to help students from all backgrounds discover common points of reference that are not limited to the French language.
The discovery of neighborhoods, our architecture, our places are landmarks.
Great names of writers, great names of artists, whether they're native or from elsewhere.
Who are our builders?
"So we create projects so that they identify with all of this", explains Aïda Kamar, president of Vision Diversity.
Michel Venne of the New World Institute identified several challenges for the school board.
"For example, the transmission of what Quebec culture is, the feeling of belonging, the support of staff in the transformations we are experiencing among the student clientele", he says.
The Marguerite-Bourgeoys school board has set up a research centre which will provide tools for teachers who, themselves, sometimes come from abroad.
Rachida Azdouz, from the University of Montreal, will be the scientific director.
Preparation to run a class in a North American, Quebec context.
"Different educational strategies are what is really needed", she says.
Research will focus on inclusion from all angles: linguistic, educational, social and cultural.
